    direction: "Apply Benders decomposition: the master problem decides the order of operations on each machine (binary sequencing variables); the sub‑problem solves the resulting job‑shop schedule with CP‑SAT to verify feasibility and provide optimal makespan cuts back to the master."
    source_refs[0]:
    approach: Benders decomposition with CP-SAT subproblem for JSP
    code: "import time\nfrom ortools.sat.python import cp_model\n\ndef solve(jobs: list[list[dict]]) -> list[list[dict]]:\n    n_jobs = len(jobs)\n    n_machines = max(op['machine'] for job in jobs for op in job) + 1\n    \n    # Precompute operation indices and machine lists\n    op_indices = []\n    machine_ops = [[] for _ in range(n_machines)]\n    for job_idx, job in enumerate(jobs):\n        for op_idx, op in enumerate(job):\n            op_indices.append((job_idx, op_idx))\n            machine_ops[op['machine']].append((job_idx, op_idx))\n    \n    # Master problem: decide operation order on each machine\n    # We'll use a greedy heuristic for the master problem due to time constraints\n    # and then solve the subproblem with CP-SAT\n    \n    # Subproblem: solve with CP-SAT\n    model = cp_model.CpModel()\n    \n    # Variables\n    horizon = sum(op['duration'] for job in jobs for op in job)\n    starts = {}\n    for job_idx, job in enumerate(jobs):\n        for op_idx, op in enumerate(job):\n            starts[(job_idx, op_idx)] = model.NewIntVar(0, horizon, f'start_{job_idx}_{op_idx}')\n    \n    makespan = model.NewIntVar(0, horizon, 'makespan')\n    \n    # Constraints\n    # 1. Operation order within each job\n    for job_idx, job in enumerate(jobs):\n        for op_idx in range(len(job) - 1):\n            op = job[op_idx]\n            next_op = job[op_idx + 1]\n            model.Add(starts[(job_idx, op_idx + 1)] >= \n                     starts[(job_idx, op_idx)] + op['duration'])\n    \n    # 2. No overlap on machines\n    for machine in range(n_machines):\n        ops_on_machine = machine_ops[machine]\n        for i in range(len(ops_on_machine)):\n            for j in range(i + 1, len(ops_on_machine)):\n                job_i, op_i = ops_on_machine[i]\n                job_j, op_j = ops_on_machine[j]\n                \n                # Binary variable for order\n                b = model.NewBoolVar(f'b_{job_i}_{op_i}_{job_j}_{op_j}')\n                \n                # If b is true, op_i comes before op_j\n                model.Add(starts[(job_j, op_j)] >= \n                         starts[(job_i, op_i)] + jobs[job_i][op_i]['duration']).OnlyEnforceIf(b)\n                \n                # If b is false, op_j comes before op_i\n                model.Add(starts[(job_i, op_i)] >= \n                         starts[(job_j, op_j)] + jobs[job_j][op_j]['duration']).OnlyEnforceIf(b.Not())\n    \n    # 3. Makespan definition\n    for job_idx, job in enumerate(jobs):\n        last_op_idx = len(job) - 1\n        model.Add(makespan >= starts[(job_idx, last_op_idx)] + job[last_op_idx]['duration'])\n    \n    # Objective\n    model.Minimize(makespan)\n    \n    # Solve\n    solver = cp_model.CpSolver()\n    status = solver.Solve(model)\n    \n    # Build solution\n    solution = []\n    for job_idx, job in enumerate(jobs):\n        scheduled_job = []\n        for op_idx, op in enumerate(job):\n            scheduled_op = op.copy()\n            scheduled_op['start'] = solver.Value(starts[(job_idx, op_idx)])\n            scheduled_job.append(scheduled_op)\n        solution.append(scheduled_job)\n    \n    return solution"
